an four years later and on the other side of the world, the newly crowned Henry IV fought his way into a Paris rife with disease and decay. By 1700, Paris had become the political center of France and a major European metropolis. Known today as Tokyo, the Edo from which the Shogun ruled Japan in 1700 was the world's most populous city.Edo and Paris compares how the Tokugawas and the Bourbons crafted their states and built their capitals. It also provides rich detail about the experiences of ordinary people, covering topics from the nature of popular culture to forms of resistance to authority in both cities. In nineteen chapters accompanied by period illustrations and maps, experts from a wide variety of fields offer a vibrant portrait not of one Edo and one Paris, but of many.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh1 aBeik, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChartier, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoaldrake, William H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElisonas, Jurgis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIkegami, Eiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsherwood, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJun, Hatano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaoru, Ugawa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaoru, Ugawa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaplan, Steven Laurence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, William W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKettering, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo